segments.text: At any rate, I left in 69, went out to Great Southwest Corporation to, I was asked to come out there and set up a department that didn't exist, Department of Planning and Design, which I did.
Just take a minute to describe the Great Southwest.
Well, Great Southwest Corporation was a company that held over 6,000 acres of land, dead center between Dallas and Fort Worth.
Why is it important?
Why is it important to Texas?
Why it's Great Southwest Corp?
Well, first of all, it was probably, to my knowledge, it was the first really massive development project that was primarily oriented toward industrial development at that scale.
It also was significant because in the original people that were involved in it, you not only had the Wim family, but you had the Rockefellers, you had Vincent Ponty,
You had Sam Zisman.
O'Neal Ford was out there designing the NS6 flags.
And Candela, the famous structural engineer from Mexico, was up designing hyperbolic paraboloids, freestanding.
And there was a pulling together, a coalescing of the talent that I think had not been seen before on that type of project in this area.
That would be my answer to the question.
At the time that I went out there, the Great Southwest Corporation had been purchased by Penn Central, along with Arbita Corporation in Florida
Oh, what was the one I keep trying to forget in California?
Macco.
And at any rate, I went out there and I did do that.
And that was my first entry into real estate development.
And then Penn Central derailed itself in 1970.
And everybody practically left the company.
And when that happened, within the next two months later, I was employed.
by Raymond Asher to work on the Flower Mound New Town project, and I was employed to be in charge of planning.
I was in charge of what was called Director of Community Planning for Flower Mound New Town, which was one of the Title VII New Towns.
Oh, yeah.
And that was 6,200 acres of land.
If you, near, well, it would be west of,
yeah, west of Louisville between Interstate 35, between the two Interstate 35s that merge and go up to Denton from Dallas and Fort Worth.
The other person, major person involved in that was Edward Marcus of the Neiman Marcus family.
And I did that for about two years.
And that was quite a significant undertaking in
in Texas.
It and I think the Woodlands was the only other Title VII new town.
The Woodlands ended up being much more successful than Flower Mound did because Flower Mound unfortunately had a problem of the plan, the way the planning had been done to get to the approval of HUD.
the way in which the decisions were made, or more accurately, not made after that time.
And it ended up being just an opportunity that should have been fulfilled and wasn't.
This was another instance where I worked with Springer.
Because Springer represented the town of Flower Mound as their planter, and I essentially was the counterpart for Flower Mound Newtown.
So we worked.
trying to bring the Flower Mound New Town plan and the comprehensive plan for the 22,000 acres, as I recall, that constituted Flower Mound itself into sync with one another at the same time.
And I should add that the reason why I went into the real estate development arena was quite simply because for the same reason that I went
from architecture to planning initially.

And that was that I felt that the, well, in the case of architecture, that there was a problem as a consultant in being somewhere in the process, but having significant things happening on each side of you that could either distort what you were doing or preempt the result of what you did.
And that was certainly true in architecture.
I found the problem to be also true
in planning with some additional problems, one of which was that, number one, people really didn't take planning very seriously in this part of the country.
And number two, the politicians, many of them were actually afraid of it.
And so therefore, it ended up being an exercise of planners talking to one another and recommending things that
We're not really germane to what the political policymakers thought they were doing.
Real estate development, the reason I went there was recognizing those problems.

I wanted to put myself in a position where I felt I would be at the center of decision-making with respect to what went on the ground and the belief that there was probably more, at that period of time, more potential influence for the good

in creating urban or urban-related environments to be in the private sector, then in a high decision-making position, then to try to convince people from the public side that they ought to be doing something that they didn't understand.
I think Vernon and Mary Lou share that view.
Yeah.
I think I would...
I'm very satisfied that I made that transition.
I think it's...
proven to be true, although I look around Dallas and some other places and realize that it certainly is not a panacea for urban problems.
What is?
Nothing.
But it certainly is more personally satisfying.
Well, there's a lot to be said for that.
You know, you asked me the question earlier about what
I thought had been accomplished in Texas with respect to planning.
And I think I answered that, well, I'm one of those that says you look at the results and then you just determine whether the methods were successful or not.
And I would say that from that point of view, I think urban planning in Texas has been almost, across the board, unsuccessful.
In my view, all you have to do is, certainly from a comprehensive planning point of view, if not
small sector or project point of view.
We have some examples of project areas and sectors and things which are certainly exceptions.
But overall, I think one would have to stretch very far to say that much has been accomplished, particularly when you look at our major cities.
You look at Houston, which I consider to be basically unlivable, uninhabitable.
Dallas, fast approaching that.
Fort Worth is still livable.
That's only because the impact of poverty
population hasn't hit it as hard as it has some of the others.
Austin is destroying itself methodically.
San Antonio is doing the same thing.
So I think you have to say that, and I think that one of the reasons for that is that we have never had any strong mandating type of leadership at a state level for planning.
Planning in Texas at a state level is a vacuum.
Always has been a vacuum.
It runs through
counter to the spouse philosophy of state and the business interest and the politicians and the lawyers and you name it.
It's counter to all of that.
There is no imperative in Texas at a state level, and therefore there's no imperative at a local level.
We do not have planning yet, but to my knowledge, that's effective.
except maybe in a few places at the county level, although it's now, I think the legislation now exists for counties to plan.
For a long time, they were prohibited from planning or zoning or anything else.
And a few are beginning to take advantage.
I understand Collin County, for example, is about to start looking hard at a county plan and zoning and all that, and a few others have.
Even Rouse's County considered a county planner a couple years ago.

But typically what the counties have done is they've limited all of their activity if they had any to roadway planning, and that's it, and intermeshing with the State Highway Department to try to assure themselves they're going to get all the funds they want.

But I do think that if I scratch the inside of my head and try to find one good example, the only one that really pops to mind is that I think is worth looking at and worth studying and worth learning from

is the, and there may be others, but this is the one I'm aware of, is the planning that has occurred in Dallas for water supply, which was triggered by, as I understand it, and Marvin, you should talk to Marvin about this, was triggered by the drought.
And while he was still planning director, and he may have had some hand in this in 1956 or 57, something like that, when Dallas
was having to haul in water.
It was in very serious straits.

Henry Grazer, who was for many years the head of the water department, and the city of Dallas mounted a very, very aggressive planning program to bring a long-range water supply to the city, which I think has been very successful and is recognized as being successful.
The city went out and
analyzed what its needs were going to be.
They analyzed where the sources of water could come from, where they were going to have to make up the shortfall.

And the result of it was that the city went out and bought large areas of land or got long-term leases or whatever they did in remote areas from Dallas so that reservoirs could be built to supplement the water supply as needed.
And these reservoirs have continued to be built.
Dallas is one of a city in the United States which has relatively modest rainfall, which is in good shape with respect to water supply.
You were talking a bit ago about Flower Mound and the problems it had experienced, some of which were connected with HUD.
Yes.
Also, the same thing applied to
The Woodlands, they had problems with HUD getting payments and so forth, and reviews conducted in a timely way, and so forth.
So there's a basic problem.
There was a basic problem with the Title VII program, in my opinion.
It was the Achilles heel.
It was there from the beginning.
And it was not recognized.
You can take for a long, long time, and you can take all of the problems that existed with respect to selection criteria and methods of selection for projects.
and say that that was part of the problem.
It certainly was.
But the biggest part of the problem was that you had a program that was based upon some beautifully crafted legislation.
The incentive to a developer to be in that program, however, was built around the part of the program which was going to provide funds to encourage innovation, new ways of doing things,
whether for cost-effective or social reasons or physical environmental reasons.
But this was at the center of the legislation.
Unfortunately, as with so many other programs, the funding never materialized.
So what you had was a number of projects, many of which were badly conceived,
And I worked on another one you don't know about, but I was a consultant for a while when I was with Great Southwest Corporation to Floyd McKissick at Soul City.
Is that what it was called?
Yeah.
Which was a Title 70 town, which had never been approved in the first place.
It was approved for all the wrong reasons.
Basically, integration.
Yeah, and it was just...
Ridiculous.
That's a whole other take.
But anyway, I was a consultant then and made a number of trips there and wrote reports and did all that.
But there, you could see it there.
You could see it at Sea Riverside.
You could see it at the woodlands.
You could see it at Flower Mound.
You could see any number of these projects, Jonathan, wherever.
The funding wasn't there.
What happened was that the landowners and developers
Yeah, two situations happened.

You had the well-intended ones that got sucked into the program, like in Eddie Marcus in Flower Mound, not understanding that the funding would not be there to do the innovation to support all of the things, you know, that were going to make this town special.
And yet he had to put up with all of the insane bureaucratic requirements and so forth.
And so that was a losing proposition.
The other situation that occurred quite frequently was you had
of people who had political connections who were trying to unload essentially bad projects.
And they succeeded.
Most of them made a lot of money.
But I would put some of those in the same category as the ISRI 20 condo scandal in Dallas.
And so Flyer Mound, in my opinion, was doomed from the beginning to ever be what
Ray Nash and Eddie Marcus wanted it to be.
We have two other so-called new towns in Texas who we haven't talked about.
One is the San Antonio new town.
Oh, yes.
And the other is Las Colinas.
San Antonio Ranch, is that what you're talking about?
Ranch, yeah.
Well, one of the people who was at the center of Flower Mounds, also at the center of San Antonio Ranch, Mr. Bob Hanson,
And some of the problems that were created at San Antonio Ranch and some of the problems at Flower Mound come from some of the same reasons.
As far as Las Colinas is concerned, Las Colinas may very well turn out to be the most successful in the long haul of all of them, mainly because it's
Columbia, Newtown, it's got the force of will of a strong individual behind it and the financial wherewithal to pull it off.
Who is behind Los Angeles?
Ben Carpenter.
That's land that was, really the core of his land that was owned by the Carpenter family for years and years and years.
Since it's been expanded, I think it's up around what, 8,000 acres now?
Something, I really don't know.
They've purchased more land.
It seems to be very well regarded.
It is, yeah.

And there's some very good things, like the Urban Center is very, you know, there's some things I would change or not do if I were doing it, but if you think about the possible alternative that might have happened out there, I think one should not spend a lot of time worrying about what isn't there.
And I think Las Colinas has a lot of potential left in it, and...
But, and I haven't been to the woodlands in a long time, so I really don't know what's happening out there.
We conduct field trips over there frequently, because it's fairly close.
And it seems to be going along well.
The villages are filling up, and the commercial center is operating well.
As far as I know, they don't have financial problems.
Well, then the Woodlands and Las Colinas will probably be our two best examples.

But one of the interesting questions I ask myself occasionally when I think about planning development in Texas, particularly now that the state is in a definite period of economic crisis, which I do not think is going to recover from any time soon.
But I see this as the new beginning for Texas, the second coming.
The first one was in 1878 when the Reconstruction ended.

but we're going to have to go through a new one here you know the question is who if you look at the the criteria and objectives of major corporations who either expand in Texas or want to move from out of Texas into Texas which is the minority most of our
Growth comes from internal expansion.
Who wants to go to Houston?
Who's going to want to live in Houston?
Who is going to want to live in Dallas after a certain point?
Neither one of them have much in the way of character.
Austin, unfortunately, as I said earlier, is fast destroying its own character.
It was stopped 10 years ago.
10 years ago would have been a great time, or at least gotten it under control then.

And again, I guess I'm sounding redundant, but I do not see anything happening of a positive nature that's going to really redirect money and heritage in Texas towards improving and creating better urban environments that are going to be really on par with the other ones nationally that we could talk about.
until the state makes a commitment, and the state gets into it, and the state starts calling some hard shots.
Well, that's where the authority is.
That's where the authority is.
Governmentally, and that's where the power is.
It's got to happen there.
Of course, Haley's book is wonderful on that point, Land Use and the States.
It's one of my favorite books.
Well, I agree that, and I think the chances of it happening are very, very remote unless we go through a crisis that shakes, literally, the foundations of state government.
Well, I think we've seen now that state government has had to come to grips with the idea that we're inferior, that we have an inferior situation with respect to public education.
And that is magnified, or should be magnified, if it isn't in their minds by the fact that

the what's been called the rebirth of the Northeast Corridor, the resurgence of the Northeast and some of the northern Midwestern cities is there because of the underlying strength that they have, not only in their industrial base, but in their educational base.
Absolutely.
Now, Texas, I think, has been priding itself over a number of years about its natural advantages.
Mainly most people, when they said that, were talking about oil and not thinking about education or people.
It's a rude awakening.
It's going to have to be faced.
But I really think until the state faces up to the fact that it's going to have to create a climate for investment, which is going to have to pay attention to not only education,

But all the other things that are important to companies that are expanding and people want to live in a place, including what our cities are like, we're going to find ourselves in an increasingly disadvantageous position in the entire nation.
And we have so much going for us.
We have a coast.
We have mineral resources.
We have a lot of things.
surface resources, people resources, but we're going to lose more of our people resources.

We're going to see, I wouldn't be surprised to see, over the next 10 years, see a lot of out-migration of people from Texas to other places who should stay here to the benefit of the state, and I wouldn't be surprised to see that include a number of educators.
Oh, I will.
I don't know how A&M can recruit
New faculty, when they can't provide CICLEAP, for example, CICLEAP is no longer available to faculty unless you're on a 12-month appointment.
And normally those go only to administrators.
Well, as the people in my current industry would say, the real estate industry would say, well, that's just not competitive in the market.
Two years ago, I remember... What time are you supposed to be?
Oh, about 6 o'clock.
Well, it's now 6.20.
Oh, it came on very good.
We can delay that part of the thing.
Just taking a look now at this bill, you are currently in development.
You have always been in the private sector of planning and education.
Right.
and worked with the chapter here, and so forth, and with the educational foundation.
I was also on the AIP board of examiners at one time.
I forgot about that.
Yeah, you were in charge of the professional development committee with the chapter.
I forgot, and it's been a long time.
I'm currently doing what I thought I wanted to do 10 years ago, and I manage and am in charge of a real estate development company.
that's based in Dallas and owned by a Canadian family.
We have significant resources and I can call a lot of shots.
I can make decisions on what we do, where we do it, when we do it, and how we do it.
And that's something that I would never be able to do if I were at this stage in my life in Texas in a planning situation.
as a governmental planner?
Well, as a governmental planner or as a consultant.
My experience is that cities don't ordinarily listen any more to consultants than they do to their own staff.
So I hate to sound so disparaging about it, but I wish we had some more Marvin Springers around to fight the battles.
Marvin used to take on the opponents at planning the way he probably, with the same attitude he had when he was a tank commander under Patton at the Battle of the Bulge.
And Marvin is, you know, we don't have any Marvin Springers that I'm aware of in planning in public positions in the state of Texas right now.
I don't know whether none have been made in the intervening period or what's going on, or we're not attracting them.

I do know, I will say that when the city of Dallas was looking, after Alden Dale left, when the city of Dallas back during that period of time was looking for a planning director, and I went to AIP conferences and tried to help them drum up interest, they couldn't get any interest from them.
from what I would consider to be highly credible people.
Part of that, in all fairness, was tied into the Kennedy assassination and people saying, who wants to go to a city that kind of has that atmosphere, which I think was kind of unfair.
But it would be interesting to do a survey of planning directors and see how many of them
if they were given the opportunity, I mean the top ones, would come to Texas.
Because most of them probably undoubtedly are smart enough to realize that without the state umbrella of support and mandate, that they're in a very weak position to accomplish much.
They're on their own.
And they're on their own with people who are elected
to city councils, for example, and other elected positions who share the philosophy or the attitude that created that situation at the state level.
So as you can tell, I'm not overly optimistic.
No.
Bill, I want to thank you very much for the interview.
And we'll get this transcribed, and then I'll give it a pre-edit and get it back to you for your review and comment.
Fine.
Thanks again.
Thank you.
